  "opinion": "As a woman who grew up in a small town where science wasn’t really a part of everyday life for most people, I’ve seen how the gender gap in science can feel personal and real. My parents, both educated but not in scientific fields, taught me that curiosity was important, but they also didn’t push me toward anything specific. Growing up in Kansas City, I had access to public libraries and community science clubs, but I never really saw women in leadership roles in STEM fields. It’s not just about numbers—it’s about the cultural messages we receive. For example, when I was in school, girls were often steered toward more practical or 'feminine' subjects, while boys were encouraged to explore math and physics. This subtle shift starts early and can shape a person’s confidence in their abilities. I think addressing the gender gap in science isn’t just a moral imperative—it’s practical. If we want to have a future where everyone can contribute to solving problems like climate change or healthcare, we need to make science accessible to all. As a barista, I see people from all walks of life coming into my café, and I’ve noticed that many of them feel intimidated by technical topics. So, how do we fix this? By creating spaces where everyone feels welcome and supported. That means teachers, parents, and even social media influencers can play a role in showing that science is for everyone. It’s not about changing the system overnight, but small, consistent efforts to challenge stereotypes and encourage participation. I believe that with the right support, anyone can thrive in science—whether they’re a parent with two kids or someone who’s just starting out. The key is to make it feel like a natural part of life, not something that’s reserved for a select few.",
